post_text:
Dear OES Families,

This message is to confirm that an individual tested positive for COVID at Shepherd Middle School. An additional deep clean is being administered to the building.

We will be working with the LaSalle County Health Department to prevent further spread within our schools and community.

Please continue to monitor your health and stay at home if you or a member of your family develops symptoms. Contact your health provider if you think you are in need of COVID testing. Anyone exhibiting severe symptoms should contact their health provider. If your child comes into contact with COVID, please contact your health provider, the LaSalle County Health Department, and OES.

Please see Mr. Windy‚Äôs letter for more information pertaining to Shepherd Middle School.

Thank you,



Cleve Threadgill

Child's name(s)
School attending
Grade

IESA has revised their plan for fall sports. Baseball, softball, and golf will be able to have their seasons this fall.

Shepherd softball tryouts will be held on the following dates:

Monday, August 3 from 4:00-6:00 PM

Tuesday, August 4 from 4:00-6:00 PM

Wednesday, August 5 from 9:00-10:30 AM

*Players should have a current physical, concussion form, and insurance form completed. Please come to as many tryout days as possible.

Shepherd baseball tryouts will be held on the following dates:

Wednesday, August 5 from 6:00-8:00 PM

Thursday, August 6 from 6:00-7:30 PM

Friday, August 7 from 6:00-7:30 PM

*Players should have a current physical, concussion form, and insurance form completed. Attendance at all 3 days is recommended. If you cannot attend, please notify Mrs. Price at cprice@oes141.org.

We were given word today that IESA has decided to cancel the following fall sports:

Baseball, softball, golf, and cross country. We are also going to cancel soccer.
Pom and cheer tryouts are currently postponed.
A decision has not been made about any other sports at this time. This is a very unfortunate decision that had to be made, but I know IESA is looking out for the safety of our students and families. We will inform everyone as we get more information about the status of future school sports. Below is a link to the IESA website. If you have any questions, please contact me at cprice@oes141.org.

post_text:
20 - 21 Reopening FAQ - Special Education Services

Resource/ISP Services - Students who receive resource services (they typically receive most of their instruction in a general education classroom) will be able to stay an additional 30 minutes after school to receive instructional time with their case manager. Depending upon the grade level, this may be additional reading time, Primetime, related services, or time to address specific IEP goals. These students will be transported home at 12:00 (12:30 for Shepherd). They would also receive 1.5 hours of instruction/assignments through remote learning.

Self-Contained Programs - Students who attend a self-contained special education program will receive instruction until 1:30 (2:00 for Shepherd). These students will not receive instruction through remote learning.

Preschool Information will be released on Thursday, July 23rd.

post_text:
Current Preparations for the 2020-21 School Year

Ottawa Elementary is making preparations for the scheduled return to school in August. We are awaiting guidance from ISBE in order to proceed with formulating a plan. We will share our course of action with our families on Facebook and the district website after our plans are complete. At this time, we believe ISBE will be strongly encouraging some type of a physical return to school.

Some steps we have taken at this time:

Purchase of iPads for every student in grades K-8; 160 of the iPads will have built-in wifi for families who may not have wifi at home should Remote Learning be required again

Ordered 17 sanitation stations to be distributed at all 5 buildings

Ordered 17 non - contact thermometers to be distributed throughout the buildings

Ordered 12,000 masks, both cloth and disposable; we anticipate ordering more

Ordered additional had sanitizer

OES PART-TIME CUSTODIAN NEEDED

Ottawa Elementary School District #141 is seeking a Part-Time Custodian for the 2:00-8:00 p.m. shift, Monday-Friday.

Illinois School Code requires Criminal Background Checks. Ottawa Elementary School District is an Equal Opportunity Employer.

Custodians must be able to do general custodial cleaning, lift 50 lbs. or more, capable of moving large items, and ability to stand/walk for 8 hr. shifts. Must have good communications, human relations skills, and demonstrate aptitude as a self-starter. Experience in a custodial or maintenance position preferred.

Click link below for application:

http://www.oes141.org/Downloads/custodian%20application.pdf

Beginning in June we are offering virtual classroom camps for youth, ages 8-14, to explore coding, game design, editing, 3D modeling and other STEAM topics from a safe social distance at home. Head to https://blackrocket.com/online/ivc/ to see our virtual camp listing. A printable version, anouncing our upcoming art contest, is attached. These popular offerings are now open for online registration.

We are optimistic that as our region re-opens we will be able to offer in-person camp experiences, for small groups, in July & August. Be sure to like our Facebook page for updates: https://www.facebook.com/ivcccebs

We want to send a huge thank you to McDonald's of Ottawa, Subway of Ottawa, Culver's of Ottawa, and the Shepherd Middle School Student Council for providing the extra treats for our meal bags this week! The kiddos will certainly be excited to trade those in for some goodies! Thanks, too, to Mrs. Sanders for seeking and collecting those donations!

While we enjoy providing this service, it takes a great deal of time and effort to plan, prepare, and bag the meals. With the nicer weather, it may be hard to remember to pick up your order, but please try to remember to do so. Thanks :)

Ottawa Elementary Band Supporters:

We would like to thank you for your pledged support of the band program through our Fannie May fundraiser this year. Due to unprecedented circumstances we are cancelling the conclusion of our Fannie May order. Our band families were asked to collect money at the same time the chocolate was scheduled to be delivered. However, if you paid in advance, we have asked our families to reach out to you. This should be a very small number, but we want to make sure you are being reimbursed if an advance payment was made. Once again, thank you for your continuous support of the OES band program. We hope to have your support for our Fannie May fundraiser next spring!

Thank you,

Mr. Chamberlin

Mr. Marxman

post_text:
Due to COVID-19, we will temporarily be holding IEP and 504 meetings via phone and video conferencing. Case managers will be reaching out to you close to your meeting date with a Google Hangouts/Meet link or a phone number to call to allow members of our IEP and 504 teams to participate in the meeting. Here's how to join us:

Pick your method:

AUDIO ONLY - Call us at the date/time of the scheduled meeting with the provided unique phone number and access code. You may use a landline or a cell phone.

- or -

VIDEO - Allows you to see members of the IEP team who have also chosen this option. You may use:

Cell phone - you will need to download the Meet (google) app and can join us for video at your scheduled meeting time.

Computer - copy and paste the hangouts meet code into the Hangouts or Meet apps on your MacBook from the little Google apps.

If you are not successful in joining us for the meeting, we will call you and invite you to join us.

post_text:
3-13-2020

12:30 p.m.

Dear OES Families,

On Monday, March 16th OES will have a half day of school for the purpose of preparing for the possibility of E learning (electronic learning) days. Students in grades K-6 will dismiss at 11:30 a.m. Shepherd students will dismiss at 12:10 p.m.

At this time, school is still scheduled for student attendance throughout next week as mandated by the governor. If anything were to change, we will alert our families immediately.

A Blackboard phone message will be sent later today to families. To clarify, this is not a notice of cancellation of school next week; it is for the purpose of holding a half day inservice on Monday to prepare for the possibility of E learning.

Thanks,

Cleve Threadgill

Shepherd Middle School

Giving Tree

Tis the Season of giving- Take an envelope to make a donation to either Ottawa PADS or Ottawa‚Äôs Feed His Children. Mark your envelope to indicate where you would like your donation to go and turn it into the cashier or drop it off at Shepherd Middle School.

***If you would like to sponsor a child(ren) this holiday season, please contact Lori Sanders at 815-434-7925 Etx. 5003

PADS

Our local homeless shelter (PADS) is always in need of funding and support. Checks can be made payable to ‚ÄúOttawa PADS‚Äù

Feed His Children

Crossbridge Community Church of the Nazarene anonymously provides food to local families through a program called ‚ÄúFeed His Children‚Äù- This program is being utilized by 29 schools and currently serves hundreds of families throughout the LaSalle County area. Checks can be made payable to ‚ÄúCrossbridge- Feed His Children‚Äù

post_text: Did you know that the National School Lunch program serves more meals in a single day than the leading fast food restaurant? Join us as we celebrate National School Lunch Week, October 15-18th. Students who enjoy a hot lunch will have the chance to win one of the goodie bags containing a stadium cup, pencil, Rice Krispie Treat and some other little treats! Winners will be listed in the November menu!

Here‚Äôs a clarification for the differences between the Bundtinis and Bundtlets that are being sold.

Bundtinis vs Bundtlets
$21.00 A Dozen
Bundtinis are about the size of a cupcake, so they may be a bit larger than a ‚Äúbite-size.‚Äù They are more like three bites each. The bundtinis are being offered in the standard assortment of our top four flavors, which include 3 Chocolate Chocolate Chip, 3 Red Velvet, 3 White Chocolate Raspberry and 3 Lemon.

The Bundlets are larger in size, approximately four inches round and are $5 each.

post_text:
Sub Teachers Needed
Step 1) Register at the Regional Office to get your Substitute Authorization Form, you can contact them at 815.434.0780. After you have this form in your possession, please stop down to our District Office, 320 West Main Street and see Alison Cresto. You will need to bring your sub authorization form, Social Security Card and Drivers License or State ID. Even though the Regional Office has a list of subs, we require our subs to fill out our paperwork and we put you on our personal Sub List. If you have any questions, feel free to Contact Alison at 815.433.1133 x 6002.
